{"title_page": "1924 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe 1924 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was the 16th in its history.\n\nAt a Management Committee meeting on 9 April, the Mangere United team, and [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] clubs who had requested to enter senior teams in the First Grade competition were accepted, bringing the total number of teams to nine. The suggested format was one where after the first round the top six teams would continue while the bottom three teams would have other matches arranged for them.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Management Committee\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LV| issue=86\n| date = 1924-04-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240410.2.136.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-04}}</ref> However all nine teams remained in the grade until the end of the season. The Mangere United team was a combined team from the Manukau and Mangere clubs. Both clubs retained their own identity in the junior grades.\n\nOn the opening day of the season all four First Grade matches were played on [[Carlaw Park]]. The junior matches on the same day were postponed as the railway workers were on strike and there was no way for the players to reach the outer suburban grounds which were used for matches in these grades.\n\n[[Marist Saints|Marist]] won the first grade championship for the first time in their history after defeating Devonport in the final by 20 points to 17 in front of a club record crowd of 17,000 at [[Carlaw Park]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Marist Win Final Replay/Twenty Points to Seventeen/Devonport Just Beaten\n| page =6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXI| issue=18826\n| date = 1924-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19240929.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-09}}</ref> While City won the Roope Rooster competition for the 4th time.\n\n{{s-start}}\n    {{s-bef|before=[[1923 Auckland Rugby League season|1923]]}}\n    {{s-ttl|title=16th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n    |years=1924}}\n    {{s-aft|after=[[1925 Auckland Rugby League season|1925]]}}\n    {{end}}\n{{TOC right}}\n\n===Lou Brown Transfer Issue===\n[[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], the New Zealand international had played for [[Newton Rangers]] in 1922 and 1923 however at the end of the season he moved to England to play for Wigan. He had been granted a release by Newton and the New Zealand Rugby League. Upon his return he wished to play for the [[City Rovers]] club and he turned out for them despite being told by the [[Auckland Rugby League]] that he was not eligible to play for them. City were adamant that he had been fully released and could play for any team. The New Zealand Rugby League Council supported the decision but Brown played anyway. He was subsequently suspended for 3 matches. City took the extraordinary step of withdrawing its team from the competition and they defaulted their Round 9 match with Mangere United.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Mankukau Change Over, \n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LV| issue=165\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240710.2.74\n| accessdate = 2020-03-26}}</ref> On 18 July Newton held a special board meeting and agreed to grant Brown a transfer and thus the issue was finally settled.\n\n===Manukau Rovers Club Switches to Rugby Union===\nThe entire [[Manukau Magpies|Manukau Rovers]] club switched to rugby union after a dispute with Auckland Rugby League. The issue arose after one of their players (\"King\") was suspended for four playing Saturdays. He had been suspended because he was registered with the Manukau club but \"suddenly joined, or played, for a Mangere team without having been granted a transfer\". An opposing team had protested and King had also moved back to the Manukau team. The Manukau club took exception to the decision and refused to play any of its six teams in the following grades: Second, Third, Fourth, Fifth, Sixth A, and Sixth B. It then went a step further by switching the rugby union with the Auckland Rugby Union accepting the club.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Manukau Change Over/The Reason Why/Exception Taken to League's Ruling\n| page =5\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LV| issue=162\n| date = 1924-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240710.2.74\n| accessdate = 2020-03-26}}</ref> The Secretary of the club, C. J, Williams disputed the way the Auckland Rugby League had handled the matter and several of the facts in a letter to the [[Auckland Star]]. The ARL Chairman, Mr. W. Hammill replied to the letter \"that the matters contained therein were hardly correct\".<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Why Manukau Changed Over/Management Criticised/Unsatisfactory Decisions\n| page =5\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=55| issue=164\n| date = 1924-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240712.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Goals From Marks===\nAt the ARL Management Committee meeting on 13 August the Referee's Association reported that goals from marks would no longer be permitted. This rule would come into place from Saturday, 23 August onwards.\n\n== Monteith Shield (First Grade Championship) ==\nA record nine teams competed in the First Grade competition in 1924 with the addition of the Mangere and [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] senior teams. Mangere had their colours registered as green and black. This team was essentially the Manukau Magpies club of today though they had a patchy existence for their first two decades. It was initially decided that after the first round the bottom three teams would drop out of the competition for the second round. At the end of the first round these teams were Mangere, and [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]. However this was later rescinded and all teams remained in the competition until the end of the season.\n\n=== Final Standings ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]\n|15||11||1||3||345||147||'''23'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]]\n|16||11||1||4||272||191||'''23'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|15||8||3||4||201||107||'''19'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Athletic\n|15||8||2||5||257||206||'''18'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|15||8||0||7||188||144||'''16'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]]\n|16||5||0||11||97||194||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Mangere United\n|13||4||0||9||135||244||'''8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|14||4||0||10||122||245||'''8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]\n|13||3||1||9||82||180||'''7'''\n|-\n|}\n\n=== First Grade Fixtures ===\n======Round 1======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 26 April\n| time = 1:30\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 24\u20135\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Four Senior Matches/Interesting Contests\n| page =4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXI| issue=18694\n| date = 1924-04-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19240428.2.7.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-09}}</ref>\n| away = Mangere\n| try1 = Cooke, Moore, J Shirley, Mormon, Wilfred McNeil, [[Ivan Littlewood]]\n| con1 = [[Frank Delgrosso]] 2\n| pen1 = [[Frank Delgrosso]]\n| try2 = Lipscombe\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = J Pai\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance = 4500\n| referee = Gallagher\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 26 April\n| time = 3:15\n| home = City\n| score = 17\u20132\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Four Senior Matches/Interesting Contests\n| page =4\n| work=[[The New Z